First, we need to find the intersection of B and {3}. The intersection is the set of elements that are common to both sets. In this case, the intersection is:

B ∩ {3} = {3}

Now, we can find the Cartesian product of A and (B ∩ {3}). The Cartesian product of two sets is the set of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a is an element of the first set (A) and b is an element of the second set (B ∩ {3}). In this case, the Cartesian product is:

A × (B ∩ {3}) = {(1, 3), (2, 3), (3, 3)}

So, the Cartesian product of A and (B ∩ {3}) is {(1, 3), (2, 3), (3, 3)}.
